The paper discusses a framework for robots to interpret natural language commands and act upon them in real-world settings. This involves handling linguistic diversity, associating language elements with objects in the environment, and modeling complex linguistic structure. These topics are relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including artificial intelligence (cs.AI), robotics (cs.RO), computational linguistics (cs.CL), machine learning (cs.LG), and computer vision (cs.CV). Given the focus on robotics and natural language understanding, cs.AI and cs.RO are the most likely categories, followed by cs.CL for the linguistic aspects, and then cs.LG and cs.CV for the machine learning and computer vision components.
